{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658582"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:51:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:51:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20778"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20778"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.05,0.1,0.35,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95956"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13653"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20778"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78696"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11653"},{"type":"tags","id":"11717"},{"type":"tags","id":"12627"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32861"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32862"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95956"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most accurate description of herpes simplex virus infections?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["HSV-1 is the predominant cause of genital herpes","Neonatal HSV infection is usually mild and self-limiting","Herpes stromal keratitis results from direct viral cytolysis","Cowdry type A inclusions are pathognomonic for HSV infection","Cold sores typically follow dermatome distribution"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECowdry type A inclusions are pathognomonic for HSV infection\u003C/strong\u003E. These large, pink to purple intranuclear inclusions consist of viral replication proteins and virions at various stages of assembly that push the host cell chromatin to the edges of the nucleus. The presence of these inclusions, along with multinucleated syncytia formed by cell fusion, is a characteristic histopathological finding in HSV infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECold sores typically follow dermatome distribution\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect. Cold sores or fever blisters caused by HSV-1 typically occur around mucosal orifices like the lips and nose. Their distribution is frequently bilateral and independent of skin dermatomes. Herpes zoster (shingles), caused by varicella-zoster virus, follows dermatome distribution.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes stromal keratitis results from direct viral cytolysis\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect. Herpes stromal keratitis is characterized by infiltrates of mononuclear cells and is caused by an immunologic reaction to HSV infection, not by the direct cytopathic effects of the virus. In contrast, herpes epithelial keratitis shows typical virus-induced cytolysis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHSV-1 is the predominant cause of genital herpes\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect. Genital herpes is more often caused by HSV-2 than by HSV-1, although HSV-1 can also cause genital infections.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeonatal HSV infection is usually mild and self-limiting\u003C/strong\u003E - This is incorrect. Although neonatal HSV infection (usually HSV-2) may occasionally be mild, it more commonly presents as a fulminating infection with generalized lymphadenopathy, splenomegaly, and necrotic foci throughout multiple organs including the lungs, liver, adrenals, and central nervous system.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHSV infections can range from self-limited lesions like cold sores and gingivostomatitis to severe manifestations such as encephalitis and disseminated disease, particularly in immunocompromised individuals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Herpes simplex virus type 1 (HSV-1) primarily causes orofacial lesions while HSV-2 typically causes genital lesions, though crossover can occur.","HSV-infected cells contain Cowdry type A intranuclear inclusions and can form multinucleated syncytia.","HSV infections range from self-limited lesions to life-threatening disseminated disease, with severity often dependent on host immune status."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 8; pages 354-355."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78696"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20778"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78696"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-30T13:28:18+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-30T13:29:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13653"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95956"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11653"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Infectious diseases","synonym